explanation:
Needed to decide if the controlling expression "sem_destroy(&impl->id) < 0" is invariant:

- sem_destroy: Key to the controlling expression. Its prototype, semantics and whether it has side effects determine if the call can return different values across invocations. If sem_destroy is a pure constant-returning macro/function it could make the expression invariant; if it has side effects or depends on impl->id state it is not invariant.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: This macro/function supplies the impl pointer from the object table. Its expansion may be compile-time constant or may invoke code (e.g. index lookup) that affects whether impl (and thus impl->id) is varying. Need its definition to know if impl->id is invariant.

- OS_impl_count_sem_table: The table passed into OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET may be a constant global or something that makes the lookup deterministic/invariant. Its type/definition helps determine whether impl varies.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Static call graph shows this is the usual helper used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; include its implementation to see whether the lookup uses only token (which might be constant) or has side effects.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type (and any semantics of dereferencing *token) are needed to know whether the index/value used to fetch impl can vary; if token is constant or encodes a constant index the overall expression might be invariant.

- OS_impl_countsem_internal_record_t: The struct definition is required to know the type and properties of impl->id and whether impl is derived in a way that would make impl->id constant.

- sem_t (or the actual type of impl->id): The concrete semaphore type matters because sem_destroy operates on that type; knowing the type helps determine whether the address &impl->id refers to mutable state and whether sem_destroy can have non-constant behaviour.

- OS_SEM_FAILURE and OS_SUCCESS: The constants used in the return statements determine the effect of the conditional. Confirming their values is needed to reason if the branching is meaningful or collapses to an invariant outcome.

Together these symbols allow analysis of whether the controlling expression depends on mutable state or on functions with side effects (thus non-invariant), or whether it can be resolved to an invariant at compile time.
